**SongMAE: Bioacoustic Encoder Model for the Classification and Detection of Birdsong Units**

Existing self-supervised bioacoustic encoders operate at coarse temporal scales suited for species classification and song presence detection, but lack the resolution to analyze the rapidly transitioning units of birdsong: classifying individual syllables or localizing the precise onsets and offsets of syllables and songs. We introduce SongMAE, a compact MAE-ViT (Masked Autoencoder Vision Transformer) that we pretrained on spectrograms of birdsong bioacoustic recordings. Our key innovation is the use of tall, narrow patches spanning the full frequency range but only 2ms in time, combined with Voronoi-based spatial masking to prevent the model from exploiting local correlations during reconstruction. We show that our model achieves state of the art results on three subtasks tasks, birdsong syllable classification, unit onset/offset detection, and song boundary detection. Further we show that the model is able to reconstruct masked spectrograms of a bird species it has not been exposed to during pretraining (canaries, zebra finch, and bengalese finch).

**Index terms/keywords:** 

 **1\. Introduction / Motivation** 

In the field of bioacoustics, there has been a proliferation of pretrained self-supervised encoding models. Motivated by species classification and detection tasks in data-sparse contexts, models such as BirdMAE [\[1\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/EW95), AVES [\[2\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/4TMb) and BEAT [\[3\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/4R1T) have been pretrained on large corpora of bioacoustic data. These models are applied to tasks operating on multi-second windows (typically 5 seconds): classifying which species is singing and detecting whether a song is present. While state-of-the-art for these temporally coarse tasks, they were not designed to represent the individual components of song, such as notes, syllables, or calls. These song elements transition within milliseconds and last only tens of milliseconds, yet tasks like detecting precise syllable onsets and offsets or classifying syllable types demand exactly this temporal granularity. Creating useful embeddings for these fine-grained song elements remains an open problem requiring models specialized for rapid temporal structure.

All current bioacoustic embedding models segment audio, either via 1D convolution of raw samples (Whisper, HuBERT; used in WhisperSeg, AVES) [\[2,4,5\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/9GdW+4TMb+6v0J) into tokens, or in the case of ViT-like models, spectrograms into patch embeddings [\[6\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/bUqu). A fundamental trade-off in temporal resolution exists: species classification tasks benefit from coarse resolution, which reduces the memory footprint given transformers' quadratic attention scaling. However, tokens or patches then represent temporal spans that exceed birdsong's shortest syllables and inter-syllabic gaps. The models are then inadequate for song structure analysis which requires fine-grained resolution to capture the rapid acoustic transitions defining individual vocalizations. No general bioacoustic models optimize for such resolution. TweetyBERT [\[7\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/aES7L) demonstrates the value of high temporal resolution for syllable discovery but remains canary-specific. Furthermore, the TweetyBERT approach applies masks spanning all frequencies in specific timeblocks, which removes the flexibility of experimenting with masking only portions of frequencies \-- which we believe is important for pretraining on species with non stereotyped song. Non-deep ML approaches for granular birdsong analysis exist, but they suffer from a low representational capacity [\[8\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/UGwn).

To address this gap, we introduce SongMAE, a Masked Autoencoder (MAE) vision transformer (ViT) pretrained on a portion of the BirdSet dataset. Our scope is to test whether a general syllable-level model can learn representations that generalize to species and recording environments outside its training set, using canaries, Zebra Finch, and Bengalese Finch (for which we have high-quality labels) as our test case. Our key technical innovation lies in spectrogram generation and patch parameters: we compute spectrograms with 2ms time bin resolution and employ asymmetric patches of 32 mels × 1 time bin that preserve fine temporal granularity. Despite never being pretrained on domesticated canary, Zebra and Bengalese Finch vocalizations, SongMAE generates meaningful syllable-level representations for these species, allowing it to be finetuned to detect and classify syllable onset and class with a high degree of accuracy with relatively few samples, as well as producing unsupervised UMAP embeddings that spatially segregate human-annotated syllables in embedding space.

**3 Related Work**

With respect to masked autoencoders, [\[9\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/KsSG) demonstrated that asymmetric patches favoring temporal resolution (16 mels × 8 timebins, 16 mels × 4 timebins) outperformed square (16 mels ×16 timebins) patches across most audio tasks, with particularly strong gains in speech and music recognition. It has also been observed that for speech tasks, as opposed to audio event tasks, full frame level patches (spanning all mel bins) proved to be superior [\[10\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/ywEJ). Research on wav2vec2 has shown that reducing temporal resolution while maintaining model size degrades performance, though this can be mitigated by increasing model capacity [\[11\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/KXLT). 

**3\. Methods**

**3.1 Architectural Overview:**  
SongMAE follows the canonical Masked Autoencoder (MAE) architecture, consisting of an asymmetric encoder-decoder design, and it operates on spectrograms [\[12,13\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/c8Ic+liwI). The representation is learned through a self-supervised reconstruction task: spectrograms are divided into patches through a convolutional operation, positionally encoded, and then randomly masked. The encoder processes only the non-masked patches and passes these encoded representations, along with learned mask placeholder patches, to the decoder. The decoder then reconstructs the original masked patches using mean squared error loss.

**3.2 Patch Parameters and Masking:** 

| ![][image1]![][image2] |
| :---- |
| **Figure 1:** SongMAE reconstructions of canary song. (Top) Canary spectrogram. (Middle) Random masks applied to spectrograms prior to forward pass. (Bottom) The output of the model from the decoder overlayed on top of the original spectrogram |

Birdsong shares speech's characteristic of discrete, rapidly transitioning acoustic units. However, unlike human speech, birdsong operates on timescales approximately 10 times faster. Most self-supervised audio models employed in bioacoustics are directly derived from those used in human speech analysis and thus may be insufficient for analyzing fast-changing bird syllables. The key architectural innovation in SongMAE is the use of asymmetric patches optimized for fine temporal resolution. Unlike square patches (16×16) used in standard audio MAEs, which span 160 ms, we employ rectangular patches of 32 mel bins × 1 timebin. Combined with our 2 ms spectrograms (versus BirdMAE's 10 ms bins), SongMAE achieves 80× finer temporal resolution than existing bioacoustic MAE models [(Schwinger et al. 2025\)](https://paperpile.com/c/BtVTOE/4YS4). This comes at the cost of reduced frequency resolution (32 mel bins per patch versus 16), a tradeoff necessary to maintain manageable sequence lengths given GPU memory constraints, and something we aim to experiment with in further studies.

Our masking strategy employs Voronoi-based spatial masking to address the challenge of fine-grained temporal-frequency patches, where existing approaches like random masking fail to prevent trivial reconstruction through local correlations \[source\]. We initialize seed patches (controlled by parameter C, set to 0.1, representing the percentage of masks that serve as seeds) and compute Euclidean distances from all patches to these seeds, accounting for patch dimensions. By masking the 75% of patches closest to any seed, we create irregular, connected regions that force the model to learn both local and global dependencies without relying on simple interpolation. This approach remains agnostic to patch size while requiring only a single interpretable parameter (C) to control mask granularity, avoiding the limitations of fixed-shape chunk masking that poorly adapts to asymmetric patch dimensions.

### **3.3 Pretraining and Test Dataset**

The pretraining dataset consists of the XCM subset of the BirdSet dataset [\[14\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/E8uR), derived from Xeno-Canto recordings [\[15\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/fn4Ek), this totalled 89,798 recordings. We split the pretraining set into 95 percent train and 5 percent validation to monitor overfitting. 

For the evaluation of the model, we obtained high quality ground truth syllable level labels from laboratory-recorded datasets for canary [(Cohen et al. 2022\)](https://paperpile.com/c/BtVTOE/G7l0), Bengalese Finch [(Nicholson et al. 2023\)](https://paperpile.com/c/BtVTOE/A1mx), and Zebra Finch [(Koch et al. 2024\)](https://paperpile.com/c/BtVTOE/P27Y). The test dataset totalled 8014 recordings.  None of the songbird species from these datasets were present in the pretraining dataset. 

**3.4 Spectrogram Generation:**

Audio files are resampled to 32 kHz and converted to 128-dimensional log-mel spectrograms. We use an FFT size of 1024 with a hop length of 64 samples, producing time bins of 2ms. Spectrograms are normalized using dataset-wide z-scoring statistics (mean: \-50.14, std: 20.66). During pretraining, spectrograms are segmented into fixed contexts of 1024 time bins (2.048 seconds), with shorter segments zero-padded as needed.

### **3.5 Training Details**

We adopt a 75% masking ratio and train for 500,000 batches using the AdamW optimizer with a learning rate of 3e-4, 1000 warmup steps, and a cosine annealing schedule decaying to 1e-5 [\[16,17\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/xody+w2xY). The reconstruction loss follows the standard MAE approach: patch-wise MSE computed only on masked patches. We use a batch size of 256 and enable automatic mixed precision training for training speed and efficient memory usage [\[18\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/2vz8).

**4\. Experiments**

**4.1 Evaluation Tasks and Metrics**

| ![][image3] |  |
| :---- | :---- |
| Figure 2a Theoretical Maximum Scores based on temporal resolution. Note the interesting plateau of acc of canary song, this is because … | Figure 2b: AVES straddling syllables, silences.  |

We evaluate models on two tasks representative of fine-grained birdsong analysis: syllable classification and unit onset/offset detection.

*Syllable Classification*. The goal of syllable classification is to identify the class of each syllable within a bird's repertoire. Notably, syllable repertoires are individual-specific; even within a species, birds develop unique sets of syllables that are not shared across individuals. A model capable of labeling syllable identity at each timepoint therefore provides substantial value for researchers studying vocal learning and song structure.

We evaluate syllable classification using the F1 score, following prior work \[X, X\]. We chose F1 over Frame Error Rate (FER), which has been used elsewhere \[X, X\], because syllable repertoires are highly imbalanced in frequency. FER does not penalize this imbalance, making it easier to achieve high scores by simply predicting common syllables.

A methodological challenge arises from the temporal resolution differences between models. Ground truth annotations provide continuous onset and offset times for each syllable along with its class label. However, all models output discrete predictions corresponding to fixed temporal spans (tokens or patches). To enable fair comparison, we adopt the following evaluation procedure: we first round ground truth boundaries to the nearest millisecond, then expand each model's discrete predictions into a sequence of 1ms frames (assigning all frames within a prediction span the same label), and finally compute the F1 score over these aligned sequences.

This procedure reveals an inherent advantage for models with finer temporal resolution. Even if two models learn equally strong internal representations, the model with coarser output resolution will produce predictions that straddle syllable boundaries or miss brief syllables entirely, resulting in lower scores. Figure 1 illustrates this effect by showing the theoretical maximum accuracy achievable at different temporal resolutions. Notably, canary song exhibits a plateau at coarser resolutions, reflecting the longer duration of canary syllables compared to other species.

*Unit Onset/Offset Detection.* For this task, we evaluate the model's ability to localize the boundaries of individual song units. The evaluation procedure is identical to syllable classification, except that prediction is binary (song unit present or absent) rather than multi-class.

**4.2 Models Comparison**

We compare SongMAE against two existing models: BirdAVES and WhisperSeg.

BirdAVES is a self-supervised bioacoustic encoder based on the HuBERT architecture, with approximately 316 million parameters in its large variant \[2\]. It processes raw audio at 16kHz and was pretrained on Xeno-Canto recordings. BirdAVES was designed for species classification and detection rather than syllable-level analysis, but its 20ms frame-level embeddings make it applicable to our tasks. We include it as a representative of current bioacoustic foundation models.

WhisperSeg adapts OpenAI's Whisper speech model for animal vocalization segmentation \[Gu et al. 2024\]. Unlike BirdAVES, WhisperSeg was explicitly designed for detecting the onset and offset of individual vocalizations, making it the only other deep learning model targeting within-song analysis. The original paper evaluates only onset/offset detection, but the model architecture supports unit classification. WhisperSeg can be finetuned to operate at various temporal resolutions; the authors focus on 5ms for birdsong, which we adopt for our evaluation.

We exclude several other models from our comparison. Bioacoustic encoders such as BirdMAE operate at temporal resolutions too coarse for syllable-level tasks (160ms patches), making meaningful comparison impractical. We also exclude supervised networks such as TweetyNET and DAS, as our focus is on evaluating self-supervised encoders that can generalize across species rather than task-specific supervised tools.

**4.3 SongMAE Ablations**

We test several ablations of SongMAE to isolate the contributions of our design choices. For masking strategy, we compare our Voronoi-based spatial masking against standard random patch masking. For patch dimensions, we test 32 × 1, 64 × 1, and 128 × 1 (mel bins × timebins). We also evaluate the effect of patch normalization on downstream performance.

**4.4 Experimental Approach**

Because of our limited computational budget, we could not evaluate the full finetuned performance, nor hyperparameter gridsearch across all of our SongMAE ablations. Instead, we have decided to utilize linear probes to evaluate the internal representation quality of the ablations, and the model with the highest scores would be selected to be evaluated for further fine tuning. It is possible, that the linear probe performance does not neatly correspond to the model that would be most effective in a SFT finetuned setting, however, since all of these models are trained with the same loss functions, and over the same exact dataset, we believe that it is indicative of learned representations.

The SongMAE linear probe performance is surprisingly good. A simple linear transformation of SongMAE embedding layer produces a high F1 score, meaning that the model has likely learned robust representations of birdsong syllables it has not even directly seen during pretraining. As expected, the typical MAE  random masking approach produces scores substantially below that of any voronoi ablations \-- this is likely due to the pretraining objective becoming trivial when the temporal patches only span 2ms.

With sufficient labeled data, syllable classification and unit detection can be solved by relatively simple supervised networks \[DAS, TweetyNET\]. However, the practical bottleneck in birdsong analysis is rarely model capacity but rather label availability. Producing high-quality syllable annotations requires domain experts to manually identify and classify individual vocalizations, a process that is both time-intensive and costly. For many species, such annotations simply do not exist, and for well-studied species, labeled datasets typically cover only a handful of songs per individual.

The value of a pretrained encoder therefore lies not in its performance given abundant labels, but in its ability to generalize from limited supervision. To evaluate this, we adopt a few-shot learning paradigm, finetuning each model with k \= {1, 2, 4, 8, 16} labeled samples per task, per individual bird, per species. This setup reflects realistic deployment scenarios where researchers may have only minutes of annotated recordings for a new individual or species and need a model that can leverage this sparse supervision effectively.

**6\. Discussion** 

Our results, although preliminary, suggest that SongMAE can learn generalizable representations of the individual components of song such as notes and syllables. Reconstructions from species entirely absent from the pretraining set demonstrate that SongMAE can infer large missing fragments of song structure from small contextual clues, something that can only be done if a strong and general representation of birdsong is learned. Visualizations and clustering of the latent space of the model demonstrate that it can be used to extract syllable-level representations of some canary vocalizations despite never being exposed to them during the pretraining process. 

These findings suggest practical applications for bioacoustic monitoring. With further refinement of the model, through training optimizations and a larger dataset, SongMAE could be used for the discovery of units of songs of species that have no human labels \-- or at least provide an initial set of soft labels for scientists that can accelerate analysis and labeling efforts by researchers. Another potential application is dialect mapping and species abundance quantification, detection in shifts and variations of specific song units or calls could be used to differentiate populations or individuals in ecological monitoring settings [(Marler and Tamura 1962\)](https://paperpile.com/c/BtVTOE/uVml). The small size of the model (approximately 14 million total parameters) makes it particularly suitable for embedded devices used in remote ecological monitoring. In such settings, computational resources are limited and internet connectivity is often unavailable. Storing months of raw audio recordings is impractical, making the model's compressed embedding outputs advantageous. SongMAE can operate entirely on-device, enabling real-time analysis in remote areas with low throughput network connectivity [(Höchst et al. 2022\)](https://paperpile.com/c/BtVTOE/tYM4). 

However, due to this investigation being preliminary and largely exploratory, before such use, there are several limitations. The primary limitation is that we have only evaluated the vocalizations of three bird species, all recorded in lab settings, and are not confident in its ability to discover units of song in other species, particularly those in noisy settings or with highly variable songs. Even though the reconstruction quality for validation species demonstrates that the model has learned meaningful acoustic representations, it is possible \- even likely \- that more sophisticated analysis methods beyond dimensionality reduction and clustering would be required to extract syllable-level structure from the model's latent space for species with more complex vocalization.

Our immediate next steps consist of exploring patch size and aspect ratios on latent embeddings and linear probes, to better understand the optimal trade-off between frequency and temporal resolution. We also want to apply this to different species to assess if completely unsupervised syllable discovery is achievable, the primary difficulty being collecting individual unit labels. SongMAE is currently undertrained, and augmentations, data curation, and increasing the size of spectrograms in the pretrain dataset will likely provide significant improvements in the model.

Cut Bits:

The key architectural innovation in SongMAE is the use of asymmetric patches optimized for fine temporal resolution. Unlike square patches (16×16) used in standard audio MAEs, we employ rectangular patches of 32 mel bins × 1 timebin. providing significantly finer temporal granularity than 160 ms patch resolution in BirdMAE [\[1\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/EW95). 

Our masking strategy deviates from the canonical approach in masked autoencoders. Masked autoencoders typically mask 75 percent of randomly selected patches, with each mask overlaying individual patches of uniform size. However, since our patches are asymmetric and only 2ms in temporal width, reconstruction of these patches could be trivial through local temporal and frequency correlations. Adjacent unmasked patches provide sufficient information to reconstruct missing content without learning meaningful representations. We implement contiguous masking, where each selected patch is followed by 31 additional consecutive masks along the temporal dimension. This forces the model to rely on longer-range dependencies and acoustic structure rather than local interpolation. Since achieving exactly 75 percent masking with contiguous blocks alone is computationally inefficient, we use a hybrid approach: first applying contiguous stripe masks, then filling the remaining quota with randomly placed individual masks.

Following the approach in BirdMAE, we use a Vision Transformer (ViT) for both the encoder and decoder [\[1\]](https://paperpile.com/c/CHTeWE/EW95). Due to our taller, but narrower patches, a spectrogram gets segmented into 8 times as many patches than it would with a standard ViT approach. Because of this, our encoder and decoder are constrained by size, and are significantly smaller than typical masked autoencoders.  We compare our model configuration to BirdMAE **Table 1\.**
